INSERT INTO `bills` VALUES (74728,'sb427',30,'senate','Petition for modification of a sentence; eligibility, procedures.',269,'<b>Petition for modification of a sentence; eligibility; procedures.</b> Provides a process for a person serving a sentence for any conviction or a combination of any convictions who remains incarcerated in a state or local correctional facility or secure facility and meets certain criteria to petition the circuit court that entered the original judgment or order to (i) suspend the unserved portion of such sentence or run the unserved portion of such sentence  concurrently with another sentence, (ii) place such person on probation for such time as the court shall determine, or (iii) otherwise modify the sentence imposed.','SENATE BILL NO. 427\r </b></center>\r <center>\r Offered January 10, 2024\r </center>\r <center>\r Prefiled January 9, 2024\r </center>\r <i>A BILL to amend the Code of Virginia by adding a section \r  numbered <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-303.03\">19.2-303.03</a>, relating to petition for modification of a sentence; eligibility; procedures.</i>\r <center>----------</center>\r <center>\r Patron-- Deeds\r </center>\r <center>----------</center>\r <center>\r Referred to Committee for Courts of Justice\r </center>\r <center>----------</center>\r  \r   <p>Be it enacted by the General Assembly of Virginia:</p>\r  \r   <p>1. That the Code of Virginia is amended by adding a section \r  numbered <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-303.03\">19.2-303.03</a> as follows:</p>\r  \r   <p><ins>§ <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-303.03\">19.2-303.03</a>. Petition \r  for modification of a sentence; \r  eligibility; procedures.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>A. Notwithstanding any \r  other provision of law or rule of court, upon petition of a person who \r  remains incarcerated in a state or local correctional facility or secure \r  facility, as defined in § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/16.1-228\">16.1-228</a>, \r  serving the sentence for any \r  conviction or for a combination of any convictions, the \r  circuit court that entered the original judgment or order shall grant a hearing \r  to determine whether to modify such person\'s sentence if such person:</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>1. Has served at least 15 years \r  of his sentence;</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>2. Has \r  not (i) filed a petition for \r  modification of a sentence pursuant to this section within the preceding three \r  years, (ii) had a sentence modified \r  pursuant to this section within the preceding five years, or (iii) \r  filed more than two petitions for \r  modification of a sentence pursuant to this section; \r  and</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>3. Has not been \r  convicted of aggravated murder in violation of § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/18.2-31\">18.2-31</a> or first degree murder \r  under Article 1 (§ <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/18.2-30\">18.2-30</a> et seq.) of Chapter 4 of Title 18.2 or had a second \r  or subsequent conviction of second degree murder under Article 1 of Chapter 4 of \r  Title 18.2.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>B. The circuit court \r  shall have authority to conduct hearings on and dismiss \r  without prejudice petitions for the modification of a sentence \r  pursuant to this section.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>No \r  petition dismissed without prejudice shall be counted as a petition \r  filed for purposes of clause (iii) \r  of subdivision A 2.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>C. Any person eligible \r  for modification of a sentence under subsection A may file a petition for the \r  assistance of counsel and a statement of indigency with the court on a form \r  provided by the Supreme Court of Virginia. The court may summarily dismiss the \r  petition if the person is not eligible for modification of a sentence based on \r  the criteria set forth in subsection A. If the petition is not summarily \r  dismissed and the court finds that the person is entitled to representation by \r  counsel subject to the provisions of Article 3 (§ <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-157\">19.2-157</a> et seq.) of Chapter \r  10, the court shall appoint counsel to represent the \r  petitioner. An attorney appointed to represent a petitioner \r  pursuant to this subsection shall be compensated at the same rate as an \r  attorney providing representation on a felony case pursuant to § \r  <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-163\">19.2-163</a>.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>D. The petition for \r  modification of a sentence shall be filed with the circuit court that entered \r  the original judgment or order on a form provided by the Supreme Court of \r  Virginia by the petitioner or by counsel for the petitioner. Such petition \r  shall allege with specificity all of the following: (i) the petitioner\'s full \r  name and date of birth; (ii) the offense for which the petitioner was convicted; \r  (iii) the date on which such offense was alleged to have been committed; (iv) \r  the date on which the petitioner was sentenced for such offense; (v) whether \r  the petitioner remains incarcerated in a state or local correctional facility \r  or secure facility serving the sentence he \r  seeks to modify and, if so, which facility; (vi) whether the \r  petitioner has previously filed any other petition in accordance with this \r  section; and (vii) the reason the petitioner is requesting a sentence \r  modification and any information in support thereof. If the petitioner fails to \r  submit a completed form, the circuit court may allow the petitioner to amend \r  the petition to correct any deficiency. Failure to include all \r  information pursuant to this subsection shall not be grounds for dismissal of \r  the petition.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>E. The Commonwealth \r  shall be made party to the proceeding. The petitioner shall provide a copy of \r  the petition by delivery or by first-class mail, postage prepaid, to the attorney \r  for the Commonwealth of the city or county in which the petition is filed. The \r  attorney for the Commonwealth may file an objection or answer to the petition \r  indicating his position within 60 days after it \r  is received from the petitioner, a copy of which shall be provided to the \r  petitioner or counsel for the petitioner by \r  delivery or by first-class mail, postage prepaid. The \r  petitioner may reply to any objection or answer filed by the attorney \r  for the Commonwealth within 30 days after receipt of such objection \r  or answer.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>F. The court shall \r  conduct a hearing on the petition within 90 days of the \r  filing of the petition. The \r  court may continue the hearing to a date more than 90 days after the filing of \r  the petition with the agreement of the petitioner and the attorney for the \r  Commonwealth. The attorney for the Commonwealth shall make \r  reasonable efforts to notify any victim, as defined in § \r  <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-11.01\">19.2-11.01</a>, of such hearing and of the victim\'s right to testify, \r  subject to the provisions of § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-295.3\">19.2-295.3</a>, at the hearing and to \r  submit a Victim Impact Statement, subject to the provisions \r  of § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-299.1\">19.2-299.1</a>, which may include information of any \r  changes related \r  to the factors outlined in § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-299.1\">19.2-299.1</a> since the \r  original sentencing. If the attorney for the \r  Commonwealth is unable to contact the victim, he shall file a written pleading \r  outlining the efforts made to notify the \r  victim. Prior to the hearing on \r  the petition, the court shall determine whether such efforts are \r  reasonable. Failure of the attorney for \r  the Commonwealth to make reasonable efforts to notify any \r  victim shall not preclude the court from considering the petition.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>G. The hearing on the \r  petition shall be conducted by the judge who entered the original judgment or \r  order unless such judge is no longer available, in which case the chief judge \r  of the circuit court shall assign the \r  petition to another judge of that circuit \r  court. The petitioner may appear by use of two-way \r  electronic video and audio communication that meets the \r  standards set forth in subsection B of § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-3.1\">19.2-3.1</a>.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>H. At such \r  hearing, the petitioner and the attorney for the Commonwealth may submit \r  additional evidence, including witness testimony and documentary evidence. Subject \r  to the provisions of § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-295.3\">19.2-295.3</a>, the court shall permit any victim to testify \r  at the hearing, and subject to the \r  provisions of § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-299.1\">19.2-299.1</a>, any victim may submit a Victim Impact Statement to \r  be considered by the court at the hearing.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>I. At such hearing, the \r  court may dismiss the petition or, upon good cause shown by the petitioner, at \r  any time before the petitioner\'s \r  sentence has been completely served, (i) \r  suspend the unserved portion of any such sentence or \r  run the unserved portion of any sentence concurrently with another sentence, (ii) place \r  the person on probation for such time as the court shall determine, or (iii) \r  otherwise modify the sentence imposed, except that no \r  modification of any term of confinement shall exceed the original term of \r  confinement imposed by the court. The \r  court may modify a sentence pursuant to this section \r  regardless of whether any mandatory \r  minimum term of confinement or \r  other minimum term of incarceration is otherwise required by \r  law. When determining whether there is good cause to \r  modify the petitioner\'s sentence, the court shall consider the following \r  factors:</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>1. The age of the \r  petitioner at the time of the offense and any relevant \r  research presented at the hearing \r  regarding development of the youth brain, the amount of time that has passed \r  since the date of the offense, and evidence of the maturity of the petitioner \r  since the date of the offense;</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>2. The age of the \r  petitioner at the time the petition was filed and relevant research presented \r  at the hearing regarding the decline in criminal behavior as individuals grow \r  older;</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>3. The history and characteristics of \r  the petitioner at the time of the hearing, including rehabilitation \r  demonstrated by the petitioner, the petitioner\'s disciplinary record while \r  incarcerated, and the petitioner\'s efforts to participate in any educational \r  or therapeutic programs;</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>4. Whether the \r  petitioner was the victim of domestic or sexual abuse at the time of the \r  offense and whether such abuse was related to the petitioner\'s commission of \r  the offense and any treatment or therapy received since the time of sentencing;</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>5. Any report from a \r  physical, mental, or psychiatric examination of the petitioner conducted by a \r  licensed health care professional that \r  has occurred after the initial sentencing hearing and any treatment received by \r  the petitioner while incarcerated;</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>6. Any testimony or \r  Victim Impact Statement presented by any victim of the offense or by a family \r  member of the victim if the victim is deceased;</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>7. Any evidence \r  concerning whether the petitioner\'s sentence was enhanced because the \r  petitioner exercised his \r  constitutional right to a trial or evidence that the petitioner was sentenced above \r  the recommendation of the original discretionary sentencing \r  guidelines;</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>8. Compliance \r  with the petitioner\'s case plan, as described by the \r  Department of Corrections operating procedures, during the five years preceding \r  the filing of the petition;</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>9. Any evidence of the \r  petitioner\'s acts of service, leadership, or mentorship engaged in \r  or developed independently by the petitioner;</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>10. Any information \r  regarding the petitioner\'s home and employment \r  plans;</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>11. Any information \r  related to support from community leaders, faith leaders, or other stakeholders \r  as deemed appropriate by the court; and</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>12. Any \r  other information the court determines to be relevant to whether the petitioner \r  has changed since the time of the original \r  sentencing or relevant to whether there is good cause for modification of the \r  petitioner\'s sentence.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>J. Within 30 days of the \r  hearing, the court shall file with the record of the case a written explanation \r  for the grant or denial of the petition and shall provide a copy of such \r  written explanation to the petitioner and to the attorney for the Commonwealth. \r  The written explanation shall address each of the \r  factors in subsection I and indicate the weight given to each factor.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>K. Following \r  the entry of an order to modify a sentence pursuant to this section, \r  within five days the clerk of the circuit court shall cause a copy of \r  such order to be forwarded to the Virginia Criminal Sentencing Commission, the \r  Department of State Police, and the state or local correctional facility or \r  secure facility, as defined in § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/16.1-228\">16.1-228</a>, where \r  the petitioner is incarcerated. When calculating a \r  sentence modified pursuant to this section, the petitioner \r  shall receive credit for any time served in any local or state correctional \r  facility or secure facility.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>L. The decision of a \r  circuit court to dismiss a petition or to modify a sentence pursuant to this \r  section shall not form the basis for relief in any habeas corpus or appellate \r  proceeding, unless such decision was contrary to law. \r  Filing a petition under this section shall not be construed to abridge, toll, \r  or modify any existing remedy, including filing a writ of habeas corpus, a writ \r  of actual innocence, or any other form of relief.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>M. The attorney for the \r  Commonwealth shall not require that a person waive his right \r  to petition for modification of a sentence pursuant to this section as a condition \r  of a plea agreement. Notwithstanding the terms of any plea agreement that \r  attempts to limit the filing of \r  a petition for modification of a sentence pursuant to this section, a court may \r  modify such sentence, provided that the \r  other requirements of this section are met.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>N. Whenever \r  a person becomes eligible to petition for modification of a sentence pursuant \r  to this section, the Department of Corrections shall notify, \r  within 30 days of such person becoming eligible, such \r  person of his eligibility along with a copy of this section, the \r  form for the fillable petition provided by the \r  Supreme Court of Virginia, and all information \r  necessary to complete such form. The notification shall \r  be provided to each eligible individual in his primary \r  language. Upon request of the petitioner or counsel for the petitioner, the \r  Department of Corrections shall provide any records, electronic and paper, \r  associated with the petitioner, without cost, including sentencing orders, \r  program enrollment and completion, security status, case plan documentation, \r  risk assessment data and evaluation, medical records, and any other relevant \r  records. A copy of any such records requested and provided \r  shall also be provided to the court and the attorney for the Commonwealth.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>O. The Department of \r  Corrections shall ensure that any counsel appointed to represent a petitioner \r  confined in a state correctional facility has an \r  opportunity to have reasonable contact with his client, whether in person, by \r  telephone, or by mail. At the request of the \r  petitioner or counsel for the petitioner, the circuit court shall enter an \r  order of transportation to transfer the petitioner to the local or regional \r  correctional facility serving the circuit court in which the \r  petition was filed so that the petitioner is reasonably able \r  to assist his attorney in the \r  preparation of the petition.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>P. No \r  fee shall be charged for filing a petition under subsection C or D.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>Q. A person convicted of \r  a crime that is subsequently repealed or for which the penalty \r  or sentencing range is subsequently \r  reduced may petition the circuit \r  court that entered the original judgment or order for modification of his \r  sentence pursuant to this section at any time, and \r  such person shall automatically \r  qualify for modification of his sentence, \r  regardless of whether good cause is shown. The court shall \r  modify the sentence to be in compliance with the penalties for the offense in \r  effect on the date of the hearing on the petition for \r  modification of a sentence.</ins></p>',NULL,108,'senate','in committee',NULL,0,NULL,'','69903b1a59bd3404e771d144f0a52750',101,3,1,NULL,NULL,'2024-01-11','2024-02-04 00:00:53','2024-01-11 23:55:14');
