INSERT INTO `bills_full_text` VALUES (1027800,73894,'SB278','2024-01-09','SENATE BILL NO. 278\r </b></center>\r <center>\r Offered January 10, 2024\r </center>\r <center>\r Prefiled January 9, 2024\r </center>\r <i>A BILL to amend and reenact §§ <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/8.01-412.10\">8.01-412.10</a>, <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-99\">19.2-99</a>, <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-100\">19.2-100</a>, \r  <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-273\">19.2-273</a>, and <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-274\">19.2-274</a> of the Code of Virginia and to amend the Code of Virginia \r  by adding a section numbered <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-87.1\">19.2-87.1</a> and by adding in Title 32.1 a chapter \r  numbered 21, consisting of sections numbered <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-376\">32.1-376</a> through <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-380\">32.1-380</a>, \r  relating to the Virginia Abortion Care and Gender-Affirming \r  Health Care Protection Act; reproductive and \r  gender-affirming health care services; prohibitions on extradition for \r  certain crimes; penalties.</i>\r <center>----------</center>\r <center>\r Patron-- Hashmi\r </center>\r <center>----------</center>\r <center>\r Referred to Committee on Education and Health\r </center>\r <center>----------</center>\r  \r   <p>Be it enacted by the General Assembly of Virginia:</p>\r  \r   <p>1. That §§ <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/8.01-412.10\">8.01-412.10</a>, <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-99\">19.2-99</a>, <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-100\">19.2-100</a>, <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-273\">19.2-273</a>, and \r  <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-274\">19.2-274</a> of the Code of Virginia are amended and reenacted and that the Code of \r  Virginia is amended by adding a section numbered <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-87.1\">19.2-87.1</a> and by adding in \r  Title 32.1 a chapter numbered 21, consisting of sections numbered <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-376\">32.1-376</a> \r  through <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-380\">32.1-380</a>, as follows:</p>\r  \r   <p>§ <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/8.01-412.10\">8.01-412.10</a>. Issuance of subpoena.</p>\r  \r   <p>A. <ins>1. </ins>To \r  request the issuance of a subpoena under this article, a party shall submit to \r  the clerk of court in the circuit in which discovery is sought to be conducted \r  in the Commonwealth (i) a foreign subpoena and (ii) a written statement that \r  the law of the foreign jurisdiction grants reciprocal privileges to citizens of \r  the Commonwealth for taking discovery in the jurisdiction that issued the \r  foreign subpoena.</p>\r  \r   <p><ins>2. A request for \r  issuance of any subpoena pursuant to this section shall \r  include an attestation, made under penalty of perjury, stating whether the \r  subpoena seeks documents, information, or testimony related to the provision, \r  receipt, attempted provision or receipt, assistance in the provision or \r  receipt, or attempted assistance in the provision or receipt of protected \r  health care activity as defined in \r  § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-377\">32.1-377</a>. If a court finds that a false attestation was intentionally \r  submitted and the subpoena did seek documents, information, or testimony \r  related to the provision, receipt, attempted provision or receipt, assistance \r  in the provision or receipt, or attempted assistance in the provision or \r  receipt of protected health care activity as defined in \r  § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-377\">32.1-377</a>, a civil \r  penalty of $10,000 per violation shall \r  apply, in addition to any other penalty as provided by \r  law. Submission of such attestation subjects the \r  attester to the jurisdiction of the courts of the Commonwealth for any suit, \r  penalty, or damages arising out of a false attestation under this section.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p>B.<s> When</s><ins> Except as provided in subsection F, when</ins> \r  a party submits a foreign subpoena to a clerk of court in the Commonwealth, the \r  clerk, in accordance with that court\'s procedure, shall promptly issue a \r  subpoena for service upon the person to which the foreign subpoena is directed.</p>\r  \r   <p>C. A subpoena under subsection B shall:</p>\r  \r   <p>1. Incorporate the terms used in the foreign subpoena; and</p>\r  \r   <p>2. Contain or be accompanied by the names, addresses, and \r  telephone numbers of all counsel of record in the proceeding to which the \r  subpoena relates and of any party not represented by counsel.</p>\r  \r   <p>D. A request for the issuance of a subpoena under this article \r  does not constitute an appearance in the courts of the Commonwealth, and no \r  civil action need be filed in the circuit court of the Commonwealth.</p>\r  \r   <p>E. The provisions of this article shall be in addition to \r  other procedures authorized in the Code of Virginia and the rules of court for \r  obtaining discovery, except that no subpoena issued in the Commonwealth \r  pursuant to this article may be issued by any person other than the applicable circuit \r  court clerk of court in the Commonwealth, in accordance with subsections A and \r  B.</p>\r  \r   <p><ins>F. \r  If a party submits a foreign subpoena to a clerk of the \r  court that seeks documents, information, or testimony that relate to protected \r  health care activity as defined in \r  § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-377\">32.1-377</a>, the clerk shall not issue a subpoena for service and shall present \r  the request to the court for action. The court shall review the foreign \r  subpoena and shall not issue a subpoena for service and shall quash any \r  existing subpoena issued by the court if the subpoena is for documents, \r  information, or testimony that relates to protected health care activity as \r  defined in § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-377\">32.1-377</a>, unless the subpoena seeks documents, information, or \r  testimony related to (i) an out-of-state action that is founded in tort, \r  contract, or statute, for which a similar claim would exist under the laws of \r  the Commonwealth, that is brought by a person or the person\'s authorized legal \r  representative, for damages suffered by the person or damages derived from an \r  individual\'s loss of consortium of the person or \r  (ii) an out-of-state action that is founded in contract, \r  and for which a similar claim would exist under the laws of the Commonwealth, \r  that is brought or sought to be enforced by a party with a contractual relationship \r  with the person that is the subject of the subpoena.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>§ <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-87.1\">19.2-87.1</a>. \r  Extradition of persons charged with certain criminal violations; prohibition.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>A. As used in \r  this section, \"protected health \r  care activity\" means the \r  same as that term is defined in § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-377\">32.1-377</a>.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>B. \r  Notwithstanding the provisions of this article, no demand for extradition of a \r  person charged with a criminal violation of law of another state shall be \r  recognized by the Governor if such alleged criminal violation involves the receipt \r  of or assistance with a protected \r  health care activity unless the \r  alleged criminal violation would also constitute a criminal offense under the \r  laws of the Commonwealth; however, the Governor may request that the state \r  demanding extradition attest to the factual and legal basis of such alleged \r  violation of the law of another state.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>C. The provisions \r  of this section shall not apply when the person who is subject to such demand \r  for extradition by another state was physically present in the demanding state \r  at the time of the commission of the alleged offense and thereafter fled from \r  such state, except that an affirmation under oath by such person that he was \r  present in the Commonwealth at the time of the commission of the alleged \r  offense shall create a presumption that he was not present in the demanding \r  state at the time of the commission of such alleged offense. Such presumption \r  may be rebutted by clear and convincing evidence by the demanding state in the \r  circuit court of the jurisdiction where such person subject to such demand is a \r  resident or is being held pending extradition.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p>§ <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-99\">19.2-99</a>. Arrest prior to requisition.</p>\r  \r   <p><ins>A. \r  </ins>Whenever<s>: (1)</s><ins> (i)</ins> any person within<s> this</s><ins> the</ins> \r  Commonwealth shall be charged on the oath of any credible person before any \r  judge, magistrate<ins>,</ins> or \r  other officer authorized to issue criminal warrants in<s> this</s><ins> the</ins> Commonwealth with the \r  commission of any crime in any other state and, except in cases arising under § \r  <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-91\">19.2-91</a>, (a) with having fled from justice, (b) with having been convicted of a \r  crime in that state and of having escaped from confinement, or (c) of having \r  broken the terms of his bail, probation, or parole<s>,</s> \r  or<s> (2)</s><ins> (ii)</ins> \r  complaint shall have been made before any such judge, magistrate<ins>,</ins> or other officer in<s> this</s><ins> the</ins> \r  Commonwealth setting forth on the affidavit of any credible person in another \r  state that a crime has been committed in such other state and that the accused \r  has been charged in such state with the commission of the crime, and, except in \r  cases arising under § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-91\">19.2-91</a>, (a) has fled from justice, (b) having been \r  convicted of a crime in that state has escaped from confinement, or (c) broken \r  the terms of his bail, probation<ins>.</ins> or \r  parole, and that the accused is believed to be in<s> this</s><ins> the</ins> Commonwealth, such judge, \r  magistrate<ins>,</ins> or other officer shall issue \r  a warrant directed to any sheriff or to any peace officer commanding him to \r  apprehend the person named therein, wherever he may be found in<s> this</s><ins> the</ins> \r  Commonwealth, and to bring him before any judge who may be available in or \r  convenient of access to the place where the arrest may be made, to answer the \r  charge of complaint and affidavit. A certified copy of the sworn charge or \r  complaint and affidavit upon which the warrant is issued shall be attached to \r  the warrant.</p>\r  \r   <p><ins>B. Any person \r  making such charge or complaint and affidavit under this section has an \r  affirmative duty to disclose to the court or magistrate any knowledge or belief \r  that the charge for the commission of the crime in another state is based on \r  the provision, receipt, attempted provision or receipt, assistance in the \r  provision or receipt, or attempted assistance in the provision or receipt of \r  protected health care as defined in § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-377\">32.1-377</a>. This disclosure shall be made \r  through an attestation stating whether such charge or complaint relates to \r  criminal liability that is based on such protected health care services. Any \r  false attestation submitted under this subsection is subject to a civil penalty \r  of $10,000 per violation, in addition to \r  any other penalty as provided by law. Submission of \r  such attestation subjects the attester to the jurisdiction of the courts of the \r  Commonwealth for any suit, penalty, or damages arising out of a false \r  attestation under this section.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>C. Except in \r  cases arising under § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-87\">19.2-87</a>, the issuance of a warrant is prohibited for a \r  charge or complaint that is related to criminal liability that is based on the \r  provision, receipt, attempted provision or receipt, assistance in the provision \r  or receipt, or attempted assistance in the provision or receipt of protected \r  health care activity as defined in § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-377\">32.1-377</a>.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p>§ <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-100\">19.2-100</a>. Arrest without warrant.</p>\r  \r   <p><ins>A. </ins>The \r  arrest of a person may be lawfully made also by any peace officer or private \r  person without a warrant upon reasonable information that the accused stands \r  charged in the courts of a state with a crime punishable by imprisonment for a \r  term exceeding one year. But when so arrested the accused shall be taken before \r  a judge, magistrate<ins>,</ins> or \r  other officer authorized to issue criminal warrants in the Commonwealth with \r  all practicable speed and complaint made against him under oath setting forth \r  the ground for the arrest as in § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-99\">19.2-99</a>, and thereafter his answer shall be \r  heard as if he had been arrested on a warrant.</p>\r  \r   <p><ins>B. The arrest of \r  a person is prohibited if the arrest is related to criminal liability that is \r  based on the provision, receipt, attempted provision or receipt, assistance in \r  the provision or receipt, or attempted assistance in the provision or receipt \r  of protected health care activity as defined in § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-377\">32.1-377</a>.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p>§ <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-273\">19.2-273</a>. Certificate that witness is needed in another \r  state; hearing.</p>\r  \r   <p><ins>A. </ins>If \r  a judge of a court of record in any state which by its laws has made provisions \r  for commanding persons within that state to attend and testify in<s> this</s><ins> the</ins> \r  Commonwealth certifies under the seal of such court<s> (1)</s><ins> (i)</ins> that there is a criminal \r  prosecution pending in such court or that a grand jury investigation has \r  commenced or is about to commence,<s> (2)</s><ins> (ii)</ins> that a person being \r  within<s> this</s><ins> the</ins> \r  Commonwealth is a material witness in such prosecution or grand jury \r  investigation and<s> (3)</s><ins> (iii)</ins> that his presence will \r  be required for a specified number of days, upon presentation of such \r  certificate<ins>, accompanied \r  with an attestation made under penalty of perjury stating whether such \r  prosecution or grand jury investigation is related to the provision, receipt, \r  attempted provision or receipt, assistance in the provision</ins> <ins>or receipt, or \r  attempted assistance in the provision or receipt of protected health care \r  activity as defined in § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-377\">32.1-377</a>,</ins> to any judge of a court \r  of record in the county or city in which such person is, such judge shall fix a \r  time and place for hearing and shall make an order directing the witness to \r  appear at a time and place certain for the hearing.</p>\r  \r   <p><ins>B. If \r  a court finds that a false attestation was intentionally submitted and the \r  prosecution or grand jury investigation is related to the provision, receipt, \r  attempted provision or receipt, assistance in the provision or receipt, or \r  attempted assistance in the provision or receipt of protected health care \r  activity as defined in § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-377\">32.1-377</a>, a civil penalty of $10,000 per violation \r  will apply, in addition to \r  any other penalty as provided by law. Submission of such attestation subjects \r  the attester to the jurisdiction of the courts of the Commonwealth for any \r  suit, penalty, or damages arising out of a false attestation under this \r  section.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p>§ <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/19.2-274\">19.2-274</a>. When court to order witness to attend.</p>\r  \r   <p><s>If </s><ins>A. Except as provided in subsection B, if </ins>at \r  such hearing the judge determines that the witness is material and necessary, \r  that it will not cause undue hardship to the witness to be compelled to attend \r  and testify in the prosecution or grand jury investigation in the other state \r  and that the laws of the state in which the prosecution is pending, or grand \r  jury investigation has commenced or is about to commence (and of any other \r  state through which the witness may be required to pass by ordinary course of \r  travel) will give to him protection from arrest and the service of civil and criminal \r  process, the judge shall issue a summons, with a copy of the certificate \r  attached, directing the witness to attend and testify in the court where the \r  prosecution is pending, or where a grand jury investigation has commenced or is \r  about to commence at a time and place specified in the summons. In any such \r  hearing<ins>,</ins> the certificate shall be \r  prima facie evidence of all the facts stated therein.</p>\r  \r   <p><ins>B. The summons of \r  a witness to testify in the prosecution or a grand jury investigation in \r  another state is prohibited if such prosecution or grand jury investigation is \r  related to the provision, receipt, attempted provision or receipt, assistance \r  in the provision or receipt, or attempted assistance in the provision or \r  receipt of protected health care activity as defined in § \r  <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-377\">32.1-377</a>.</ins></p>\r  \r   <center><ins>CHAPTER 21.</ins></center>\r  \r   <center><ins>VIRGINIA ABORTION \r  CARE AND GENDER-AFFIRMING HEALTH \r  CARE PROTECTION ACT.</ins></center>\r  \r   <p><ins>§ <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-376\">32.1-376</a>. Short \r  title; policy permitting \r  abortion care and gender-affirming health care services.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>A. This \r  chapter may be \r  cited as the \"Virginia \r  Abortion Care and Gender-Affirming \r  Health Care Protection Act.\"</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>B. \r  1. It is the policy \r  of the Commonwealth to \r  ensure that its sovereign authority to permit abortion care and gender-affirming \r  health care services within its territory or jurisdiction is not diminished or \r  otherwise infringed.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>2. It \r  is the policy of the Commonwealth \r  that all persons are entitled to provide, receive, and help others provide or \r  receive abortion care and gender-affirming \r  health care services not prohibited under the laws of the \r  Commonwealth, and that such provision, receipt, and assistance is not \r  diminished, chilled, or infringed by public or private actors.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>3. \r  It is \r  the policy of the Commonwealth \r  that its borders are open to all \r  persons who seek to provide, receive, or help others provide or receive \r  abortion care and gender-affirming \r  health care services not prohibited \r  under the laws of the Commonwealth.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>4. \r  It is the policy of the Commonwealth \r  that persons within its territory or jurisdiction shall \r  be able to discuss, in any medium, abortion care and gender-affirming \r  health care services not prohibited under the laws of the \r  Commonwealth.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>C. \r  This chapter shall \r  be construed liberally to promote the policy stated in this section \r  and throughout this chapter.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>D. \r  Any criminal investigation, proceeding, or conviction in any jurisdiction other \r  than the Commonwealth, \r  when guilt is based on the alleged provision or receipt of abortion care or \r  gender-affirming care not prohibited under the laws of the \r  Commonwealth, is contrary to the public policy of the \r  Commonwealth.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>§ <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-377\">32.1-377</a>. \r  Definitions.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>As used in this chapter, \r  unless the context requires a different meaning:</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>\"Abortion \r  care\" means all \r  behavioral health, diagnostic, medical, mental health, pharmaceutical, \r  preventative, psychiatric, psychological, rehabilitative, supportive, surgical, \r  and therapeutic care, services, and supplies related to the termination of a \r  pregnancy, except for the purpose of producing a live birth.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>\"Abusive \r  litigation\" means (i) \r  litigation or other legal action intended to deter, \r  prevent, sanction, or punish any \r  person engaging in protected health care activity by prosecuting any action in \r  any jurisdiction other than the Commonwealth where liability, in whole or part, \r  directly or indirectly, is based on protected health care activity that \r  occurred in the Commonwealth, including any action in which liability is based \r  on any theory of vicarious, joint, \r  or several liability derived therefrom. A lawsuit shall be considered to be based \r  on conduct that occurred in the Commonwealth if any part of any act or omission \r  involved in the course of conduct that forms the basis for liability in the \r  lawsuit occurs or is initiated in the Commonwealth, whether or not such act or \r  omission is alleged or included in any pleading or other filing in the lawsuit, \r  or (ii) attempting to \r  enforce any order or judgment issued in connection with any such action by any \r  party to an action described in clause (i) \r  or any person acting on behalf of a party to the action.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>\"Gender-affirming \r  care\" means all \r  behavioral health, diagnostic, medical, mental health, pharmaceutical, \r  preventative, psychiatric, psychological, rehabilitative, supportive, surgical, \r  and therapeutic care, services, and supplies related to supporting a person\'s \r  gender identity or to the treatment of gender dysphoria.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>\"Law-enforcement \r  officer\" means \r  those persons identified in the definitions of this term \r  in § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/9.1-101\">9.1-101</a> and subsection G of \r  § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/18.2-57\">18.2-57</a>.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>\"Menstrual \r  health data\" means any information, recorded in any form or medium, that \r  is created or received by an entity that relates to or is used to determine, \r  predict, or estimate the past, present, or future menstrual health or menstrual \r  status of an individual.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>\"Protected \r  health care activity\" \r  means abortion care and gender-affirming health care services that are lawful \r  in the Commonwealth.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>\"Provision\" and \r  \"receipt\" \r  of abortion care and gender-affirming \r  care mean the providing of such care, the receiving \r  of such care, the assisting \r  in the providing or receiving of such \r  care, or materially \r  supporting the providing or receiving of such care.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>§ <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-378\">32.1-378</a>. \r  Abusive litigation; interference with protected health care activity.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>A. Any \r  person who sustains any injury, damages, or other harm resulting \r  from another person who, under the law \r  of a jurisdiction other than the \r  Commonwealth of Virginia, \r  engages or attempts to engage in abusive litigation may \r  bring a civil action against any person who engages or attempts to engage in \r  such abusive litigation.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>Each legal \r  action that involves \r  abusive litigation constitutes a \r  separate liable act.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>B. Any \r  person who is found to be liable for engaging or attempting to engage in \r  abusive litigation shall be \r  liable for the actual damages suffered \r  or $2,500 per act, \r  whichever is greater.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>Actual damages \r  may include (i) all costs, expenses, reasonable fees for retained experts, and \r  reasonable attorney fees incurred as a result of abusive litigation, as \r  incurred by the person filing the civil action, \r  and (ii) the reasonable value of any emotional, physical, societal, financial, \r  and business harm suffered as a result of abusive litigation, as suffered by \r  the person filing the civil action.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>C. \r  Notwithstanding any other provision of \r  law, a civil action under this section \r  may be brought within two \r  years from the discovery of any violation \r  of subsection A.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>D. \r  This section shall not apply to a lawsuit or judgment entered in another jurisdiction \r  that is based on conduct for which a cause of action exists under the laws of \r  the Commonwealth if the course of conduct that forms the basis for liability \r  had occurred entirely in the Commonwealth, including any contract, tort, common \r  law, or statutory \r  claims.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>§ <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-379\">32.1-379</a>. \r  Law-enforcement investigations related to abortion care, gender-affirming care, \r  and menstrual health data.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>A. \r  Notwithstanding any other provision of \r  law, no law-enforcement officer acting in the \r  Commonwealth or employed by the Commonwealth or any of its localities or \r  political subdivisions may investigate, arrest, or detain any person, seek the \r  issuance of a warrant, or otherwise assist in or provide support for any \r  investigation regarding either the provision or receipt of abortion care or \r  gender-affirming care not prohibited under the laws of the \r  Commonwealth or any person\'s \r  menstrual health data.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>B. \r  Notwithstanding any other provision of \r  law, no law-enforcement officer acting in the \r  Commonwealth or employed by the Commonwealth or any of its localities or \r  political subdivisions may provide information to any \r  law-enforcement officer of any other jurisdiction or any private citizen, \r  relating to either abortion</ins> <ins>care or gender-affirming care not prohibited under \r  the laws of the Commonwealth or \r  any person\'s menstrual \r  health data.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>C. Any person who \r  is the subject of any investigation subject to subsection A or who is the \r  subject of any information subject to subsection \r  B may bring a civil action to enforce the terms of this section. \r  The only relief that may be awarded in a civil action brought under this \r  subsection is declaratory, injunctive, or other equitable \r  relief. No monetary damages, penalties, costs, expenses, expert fees, or \r  attorney fees may be awarded in any such action.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>D. Notwithstanding \r  any other provision of law, a civil \r  action under this section \r  may be filed in the court for the city or county where the person filing suit \r  resides, has their principal place of business, or in the courts for the City \r  of Richmond.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>§ <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/32.1-380\">32.1-380</a>. \r  Waiver of immunity.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>A. The \r  Commonwealth, its agencies, \r  localities, and political \r  subdivisions, and all officers, employees, and agents of the Commonwealth, its \r  agencies, its localities, and its political subdivisions, \r  waives immunity as to the imposition of declaratory, injunctive, or other \r  equitable relief for any action brought pursuant \r  to this chapter.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>B. If \r  an officer, employee, or agent of a government or governmental entity engages \r  in conduct prohibited or made unlawful under this chapter, \r  in the course of their employment, under the color of law, or pursuant to their \r  duties on behalf of the government or governmental entity, that officer, \r  employee, or agent may be held liable or otherwise subject to court order as \r  authorized in this chapter, \r  in their individual capacity, as if they had not been acting in the course of \r  their employment, under the color of law, or pursuant to their duties on behalf \r  of the government or governmental entity.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p><ins>C. The provisions \r  of this section shall not be construed \r  to waive any immunity regarding the \r  imposition of damages, costs, expenses, expert fees, attorney fees, or other \r  monetary relief for the \r  Commonwealth, its agencies, localities, and political subdivisions, and all \r  officers, employees, and agents of the Commonwealth, its agencies, its \r  localities, and its political subdivisions.</ins></p>\r  \r   <p>2. That the provisions of this act may result in a net \r  increase in periods of imprisonment or commitment. Pursuant to § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/30-19.1:4\">30-19.1:4</a> of \r  the Code of Virginia, the estimated amount of the necessary appropriation \r  cannot be determined for periods of imprisonment in state adult correctional \r  facilities; therefore, Chapter 1 of the Acts of Assembly of 2023, Special \r  Session I, requires the Virginia Criminal Sentencing Commission to assign a minimum \r  fiscal impact of $50,000. Pursuant to § <a href=\"http://law.lis.virginia.gov/vacode/30-19.1:4\">30-19.1:4</a> of the Code of Virginia, the \r  estimated amount of the necessary appropriation is $0 for periods of commitment \r  to the custody of the Department of Juvenile Justice.</p>',0,'2024-01-10 01:36:29','2024-01-10 01:38:07');
