INSERT INTO `comments` VALUES (15985,90203,73202,'Amy Tankoos','example@example.com',NULL,'127.191.98.90','Here\'s what you need to add to this bill.  REQUIRE that animal control agencies that have their own shelters come and pick up cats/kittens that citizens report as abandoned and not feral.  I volunteer at a cat rescue in the Richmond area and we get requests from citizens about helping them rescue lost/abandoned social (tame) cats because ANIMAL CONTROL won\'t come and pick them up.  Isn\'t that their job?  This bill sounds like it codifies regulations in regards to cat colonies but says nothing about cats that are abandoned by their owners into these colonies who then are encountered by neighbors to the colonies or who are found around homes/apartments/places of business and clearly are someone\'s lost or abandoned pet.  When reported to Animal Control they do nothing.  This bill should require Animal Control to respond to citizen reports of lost/abandoned animals by coming to investigate and if the animals are found, removing them to the safety of the shelter.','comment','published','n','2024-01-06 14:28:21','2024-01-06 14:28:21'),(15991,90214,73202,'Delano Erwin','example@example.com',NULL,'127.13.138.156','I am happy to see this bill. It’s past time to have regulations for cats that kill and maim millions of birds and small mammals annually. Cats constantly roam my yard killing birds. Why aren’t there leash laws for cats as well as dogs.','comment','published','n','2024-01-10 12:52:30','2024-01-10 12:52:30'),(16126,90340,73202,'Theresa Owens','example@example.com',NULL,'127.91.11.12','Rather than making TNR more difficult there should be more funding.','comment','published','n','2024-01-22 21:16:37','2024-01-22 21:16:37'),(16127,90343,73202,'Catherine Ross','example@example.com',NULL,'127.18.224.175','I strongly oppose HB 221 regarding a free-roaming cat management plan. This bill threatens to undermine successful programs of Trap-Neuter-Vaccinate-Return already occurring throughout Virginia and puts the lives of unowned cats at risk. HB 221 is unclear, lacks transparency, and does not prioritize non-lethal methods of cat population management. If passed, additional regulations will serve to further burden an already strained system. If the legislative body is concerned about a growing population of free roaming cats then increase state funding for high volume spay/neuter programs. Communities cannot euthanize their way to eliminating the cat population but numbers will dwindle with sterilization.','comment','published','n','2024-01-22 23:41:30','2024-01-22 23:41:30'),(16128,90350,73202,'Elke Landenberger','example@example.com',NULL,'127.16.202.2','The root cause of unwanted cat populations is the fact that there is no law in Virginia that stipulates that pet owners need to sterilize their pets, as is common in other U.S. states or European countries. Thousands of cats and dogs are being killed at shelters every year in Virginia because their owners allowed their pets to breed indiscriminately. This would prevent thousands of unwanted kittens (and puppies) to be born and abandoned, adding to the population since most of them never received the proper vet care, including spay/neuter surgeries. \n\nWhat this bill also lacks is the responsibility of animal care agencies to investigate and take in abandoned pets at apartment complexes, closed up hotels, and shopping areas, to name a few localities. Funding for shelters also seems inadequate since so many well-meaning citizens are turned away when they report finding a lost or abandoned pet, putting the financial burden on good Samaritans to care for the animal, just because the shelter is already filled to capacity and new foster homes are not available. This burden should not fall on the average citizen just because they have a caring heart but needs to be supported by state-funded agencies. \n\nFunding for TNR programs would also be helpful since the TNR clinics I use are always based on donations and volunteer staff. This set-up does have an impact on the unwanted cat population but so much more could be accomplished by having funding available to sterilize larger numbers of cats. Killing unwanted cats is inhumane and not supported by the majority of the population but as long as the cause is not addressed, we will still deal with the same problem decades down the line. I can only hope that the will to deal with the immense number of pets being intact and allowed to breed will be officially addressed and prevented by demanding that pet owners spay and neuter their pets, just as we expect our pets to have proof of rabies vaccinations.','comment','published','n','2024-01-23 14:43:40','2024-01-23 14:43:40'),(16129,90352,73202,'Jason Alexander','example@example.com',NULL,'127.7.53.4','Trap-Neuter-Return (TNR) is a successful and humane strategy for controlling and managing feral cat populations. By trapping feral cats, neutering or spaying them, and then returning them to their original location, TNR helps reduce the number of new kittens born in the wild. This approach not only curbs population growth but also improves the health and behavior of the cats, as neutered cats are less likely to roam, fight, or spread diseases. Over time, TNR can lead to a gradual decrease in the feral cat population, while ensuring the well being of the existing cats in a non-lethal, ethical manner.   As someone who works with a TNR program this bill will not help the situation and will only server to kill cats which has been proven ineffective in several studies.  The true solution is to provide funding to local TNR programs that help manage cat populations.','comment','published','n','2024-01-23 14:48:50','2024-01-23 14:48:50'),(16134,90369,73202,'Alex Matthews','example@example.com','http://NA','127.157.209.38','A harmful and uneducated regulatory bill that threatens existing methods to curb domestic cat overpopulation by hindering TNR efforts across Virginia. The effects of this bill would be more unwanted births of cats, hindrances to spay and neuter efforts, and cruelty against domestic animals, all while failing to address the root issue of cat overpopulation. This is the direct result of organizations and delegates following flawed research and attempting to develop a solution without proper scientific analysis. \n\nLets not forget the legal history of a government authority mandating and encouraging the culling of free-roaming cats. One of the indirect causes of the black plague in Europe was the cat-killing Pope Gregory IX whose cat-hating rhetoric caused massive decline in the cat population. The free roaming cats of Virginia keep the rat population down. Beyond disappointing to see organizations tout this as a Wildlife preservation effort while pearl-clutching flawed studies that take place in ecosystems drastically different from Virginia (pacific islands).','comment','published','n','2024-01-24 15:34:25','2024-01-24 15:34:25'),(16158,90439,73202,'Natalie Watson','example@example.com',NULL,'127.223.209.21','I 1st heard of this bill through a newsletter from a Wildlife rehabilitator I get and honestly, I kept searching for more info about what it actually DOES? I also very keenly noticed that it does not say the only thing that I care for it to say, which is that it will not start slaughtering healthy cats en masse.  It was worded VERY carefully and VERY OBVIOUSLY not to say anything about euthanizing cats as it will most likely do in large numbers, no matter how benign it sounds on the surface.  That\'s when you KNOW they really plan to kill lots of cats, when they dont mention it!\n\nI might be willing to work with it more if they would be upfront and honest, that yes, some cats will be euthanized but that is not the goal, at ANY POINT and had massive amounts of jail time for anyone found to be killing cats as way to get rid of local populations. By not being up front about it< i can not support this bill in any way and more importantly, it is exceedingly vague and does not meet a min. requirement for more info. on how and what the plan is.  Come back when you have real plan or arent lying about this one.  \n\nThe plan I think you should do to help wildlife is to reduce the human population so that more birds and wildlife can live.  Humans are the worse threat to their survival!  When you reduce humans, the whole world gets better as we dont have to compete for resources, which means more for wildlife.  I have studied this problem, the answer to everything is to reduce the humans (by not encouraging children, offering incentives, and abortions).  Things will be rough for a bit but then they will be really great.','comment','published','n','2024-01-30 20:36:17','2024-01-30 20:36:17'),(16160,90439,73202,'Natalie Watson','example@example.com',NULL,'127.228.192.148','What you really need to is more qualifed vets to do FREE spay and neuter to anyone making less than 40K.  That should be the new law.  ALL other spay and neuter should cost less than $100 with all the bells and whistles of monitoring for the entire procedure from bloodwork to everything.  In other words, make it massively easy and very cheap!','comment','published','n','2024-01-30 21:18:00','2024-01-30 21:18:00'),(16173,90468,73202,'Laurie M. Masserini','example@example.com',NULL,'127.97.48.119','I strongly disagree with HB 221. Im  also aware that our Bird Population has more, viruses & diseases than our \"free roaming cats\". I love both, birds and cats.\nBird Diseases need to be addressed., Not free roaming cats. Hunting Dogs need to be addressed. \n \nCats are not the main source of the loss of; or threat to our Bird Population and health concerns. \n\nBut, Pollutants, contamination, ground and water pollution, improper feeders, other wildlife predators, Pesticides used on lawns, gardens, farms, factories,  large and small are a much Larger Source of threat and Harm to all of us. \n\nWhere are your \"statistics and statements\" from All of the Trap Neuter Return Volunteers and non profit organizations?\nWhere are the statistics regarding how many cats, who have been TNVR, by all of the Vets Statewide who provide this service for the countless hard working Volunteers who have been effectively trapping for many, many, many years?\n  Where are your numbers and studies regarding how many free roaming cats have been successfully fixed, vaccinated and prevented from having more litters? TNR, truly is the only proven effective way to best control the cat communities. \nIf you spoke to, or Invited those Organizations, Shelters, Vets to speak and add their facts it\'d be extremely helpful with making any decisions to address the cat population. \n\nA novel approach and Idea would be to provide All of Our communities with the equipment, and services that could potentially help them, be even \"More \" effective than they already are.  Imagine that, volunteers, non-profits and neighborhood communities with the proper resources all working together to control and make our free roaming cats, safer, healthier and not producing litter after litter. Which will lower the numbers of community cats in time.\n \nI strongly suggest and ask you to provide the above type of alternative for helping the community cat population. \nLook at those types of results, studies and positive impact this would have over the next few years. \nSincerely','comment','published','n','2024-02-01 19:25:11','2024-02-01 19:25:11');
