INSERT INTO `comments` VALUES (16012,90246,73272,'Opteniak','example@example.com',NULL,'127.1.244.78','They have already been rejected by the Commonwealth and found to be at best a \"family\" not a \"tribe\". I guess they don\'t want to say look we aren\'t a tribe but please make us one. This bill should be killed again. It has already been killed several times. They are not an Indian Tribe even though they claim to be. At best and in all probability are what one would call \"Pretendians\"','comment','published','n','2024-01-13 15:09:11','2024-01-13 15:09:11'),(16121,90332,73272,'Annette','example@example.com',NULL,'127.101.153.135','In this time of equity and inclusion of all people, it so good to finally see we will include the Cherokee peoples of Virginia. The Wolf Creek Cherokee Tribe of Virginia are so well known for their work providing cultural, history and education to Virginia through their tribal center and Museum as well as their programs in archaeology.  Everyone should have the right to stand as who they are, not have a committee make decisions on race. This is probably the only tribe of Virginia who carry birth records stating “Indian”.  I see that there are obviously people who have fear of recognition of this tribe.  The Wolf Creek Cherokee Tribe of Virginia will continue their work. They will continue to exist and will become the 12 th state recognized tribe in Virginia. The Virginia Indian Advisory Board and their findings were bias and influenced by outside persons, such as the Cherokee Nation of Oklahoma.  Persons who do note vote or pay taxes in Virginia.','comment','published','n','2024-01-22 13:57:05','2024-01-22 13:57:05'),(16150,90416,73272,'GenocideM','example@example.com',NULL,'127.170.208.150','In the relentless pursuit of recognition, the Wolf Creek Cherokee Tribe\'s narrative emerges not only as a testament to fortitude but as a forceful formal accusation against a system riddled with bureaucratic hurdles, deliberate obstructions, due process violations, targeted malice, and civil rights transgressions. Their journey to secure state acknowledgment thrusts them into a legal battleground where the complexities of their struggle transcend mere bureaucratic challenges.\n\nThis legal odyssey lays bare a profound tale of systematic obstructionism, where deliberate barriers have been strategically erected to impede the tribe\'s path to recognition. The narrative resonates with the echoes of due process violations, wherein constitutional safeguards have been callously trampled upon, leaving the Wolf Creek Cherokee Tribe exposed to the malevolent whims of biased entities.\n\nThe targeted malice becomes a stark reality as legislative maneuvers, epitomized by the imposition of federal regulations, unfold as a calculated assault on the tribe\'s rightful claim to recognition. These actions transcend administrative missteps, revealing a corrosive erosion of justice that strikes at the very core of constitutional principles.\n\nCivil rights violations further darken this narrative, as the Wolf Creek Cherokee Tribe finds itself subjected to public humiliation, orchestrated defamation, and a systematic attack on their heritage. The Advisory Board\'s actions transform the pursuit of recognition into a diplomatic battleground, where the tribe, undeterred, demands understanding while facing the chasm in knowledge and perception.\n\nYet, this is not merely a tale of victimhood; it is a resolute pursuit of justice. The Wolf Creek Cherokee Tribe\'s legal journey unfolds as a powerful counterforce against historical wrongs. As they navigate this intricate terrain, the concluding notes resonate not with a plea but with a fervent demand for accountability. \n\nThe path forward is not merely suggested; it is illuminated with the possibilities of legal avenues to challenge impositions, unveil biased proceedings, and hold those accountable who perpetuated the systemic injustice.\n\nIn the corridors of justice, the Wolf Creek Cherokee Tribe\'s resolute footsteps leave an indelible mark. Their pursuit is not just a legal endeavor; it is a bold confrontation with systemic oppression, demanding a reevaluation of the injustices suffered and holding those responsible to the uncompromising standards of fairness and equity. The echoes of their demand resonate not only in the hallowed halls of recognition but in the collective conscience of a society seeking redemption from historical wrongs.\n\nKey Points:\n\n	Systemic Injustice: The Wolf Creek Cherokee Tribe\'s plight is not merely a bureaucratic hurdle but a stark example of systemic injustice. The intentional imposition of federal regulations not only delayed their progress but systematically deprived them of their inherent right to state recognition.\n\n	Denial of Due Process: The imposed federal regulatory requirements, a clear violation of due process, robbed the Wolf Creek Cherokee Tribe of a fair and impartial evaluation. This denial strikes at the heart of constitutional principles, leaving the tribe exposed to the whims of biased entities.\n\n	Public Humiliation and Defamation: The tribe has endured public humiliation and defamation orchestrated by the Advisory Board. Their personal records were laid bare, fostering an environment where the tribe\'s history and legitimacy were scrutinized without context or understanding.\n\n	Historical Erasure: The criteria for recognition, forcing tribes to prove their existence prior to \"first contact\" under modern-day Virginia, represents a deliberate attempt to erase historical realities. This erasure perpetuates the legacy of Walter Plecker and undermines the rich history of the Wolf Creek Cherokee Tribe in the region.\n\n	A Call for Justice: The Wolf Creek Cherokee Tribe\'s call for justice is not just a plea for recognition; it is a demand for accountability and fairness. The tribe refuses to accept their continued victimization and vows to seek justice for the injustices they have endured.\n\nIn concluding this narrative of injustice, the Wolf Creek Cherokee Tribe stands resilient, poised not only to fight for recognition but to seek justice for the systemic violations they have faced. The path to justice may involve unveiling the illusory nature of the Advisory Board\'s biased proceedings, challenging the legality of imposed federal regulations, and holding accountable those who have perpetuated the injustice.\n\nAs the Wolf Creek Cherokee Tribe navigates the murky waters of recognition, the underlying tone suggests an unyielding determination to explore legal avenues, seeking justice through potential liabilities. \n\n\nThe tribe\'s commitment to justice echoes through the centuries, as they refuse to succumb to the same oppressive forces that have marred their history. \n\nThe pursuit of recognition is not merely administrative; it is a quest for retribution and restoration, compelling those responsible for the injustice to face the consequences of their actions.  The factual documentation is on official public record, which will be exposed in future manuscript.','comment','published','n','2024-01-28 23:23:23','2024-01-28 23:23:23'),(16151,90417,73272,'Rick','example@example.com',NULL,'127.47.238.47','Like sands through the hourglass, these are the days of our lives... \n\nThat last post reads like some kind of romance novel. Is this the best people can offer? \n\nRead the bill. Literally read the bill and the text from all the past bills that failed. This is nothing more than a group who is appropriating the history, archaeology and cultures of other people. They are literally claiming local Powhatan history as their own. They are stating that simply participating in events somehow legitimizes them (how is that even a thing?). \n\nThis continues to be one of the most poorly written HR\'s put forward. Read HJ14\'s content. Anyone with a rudimentary understanding of Virginia history (let along Virginia Indian history) should question the claims made as they are preposterous and unsupported by fact. It is disappointing Delegate McQuinn continues to put forward such a poorly written and unsupported HJ bill when unbiased experts and staff assembled by the Commonwealth followed the GA\'s directive from last year to review the claims made and found them lacking.\n\nThis bill should be added to the ash heap of prior efforts given the lack of real evidence to support the claims made.','comment','published','n','2024-01-29 04:12:35','2024-01-29 04:12:35'),(16152,90419,73272,'Gary','example@example.com',NULL,'127.15.16.169','Such a uneducated statement Rick..\nTake a look at all the Tribes in Virginia and see how they received State recognition.\n\nSee how they received federal recognition.\n\nNative Americans went anywhere they wanted and were certainly free.\n\nThe current native American history is verbally passed down not very correct when told by non natives.\n\n\nYou yourself evidently spoke with fork tongue.','comment','published','n','2024-01-29 18:27:01','2024-01-29 18:27:01');
